fix: route block editor preview through Next.js, force draft slugs

The Week 5 preview button worked from the classic editor but not from
Gutenberg: the block editor computes the preview URL in JavaScript from
the REST API's post.link, bypassing PHP's preview_post_link filter
entirely. Drafts also have empty post_name by default in WP, so even
when the filter does fire there is no slug to route on.

Two changes in the nordic-works-core plugin:

- Add nordic_frontend_link hooked on post_link, post_type_link and
  preview_post_link. Published posts get rewritten to the Next.js
  public URL (/articles/<slug>, /services/<slug>, ...); everything else
  (drafts, pending, future) goes through /api/preview with id, slug and
  type so the editor's preview button reaches Next.js regardless of the
  code path used to build the link.

- Add nordic_force_draft_slug hooked on wp_insert_post_data so drafts
  of our managed post types get a slug as soon as they are saved
  (sanitize_title of the title, falling back to "draft-<id>" when the
  title is empty or all non-word characters).

/api/preview now accepts an id fallback. When the slug query is empty
it fetches the post by id over the authenticated REST API to recover
the slug before enabling draftMode and redirecting, so the
slug-less-draft edge case still resolves to the right article page.

Verified end-to-end against a Gutenberg draft post 92 ("下書きテスト"):
post.link in the REST response now points at /api/preview, the preview
endpoint returns 307 with __prerender_bypass set, and the redirected
page renders the preview banner together with the draft title.

